04622nam a22006255i 9780300185294DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20191995ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001852947 a10.12987/97803001852942doi  a(DE-B1597)486556  a(OCoLC)1083581679  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aG2445.E625b.E48 2010eb 7aREF0020002bisacsh04a381.440918212221 aEltis, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAtlas of the Transatlantic Slave Trade /cDavid Eltis, David Richardson. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2019] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b189 color maps; 5 b-w + 36 color illus.; 61 color graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Lewis Walpole Series in Eighteenth-Century Culture and History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tForeword -- tAbout This Atlas -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Nations Transporting Slaves from Africa, 1501–1867 -- tPart II. Ports Outfitting Voyages in the Transatlantic Slave Trade -- tPart III. The African Coastal Origins of Slaves and the Links between Africa and the Atlantic World -- tPart IV. The Experience of the Middle Passage -- tPart V. The Destinations of Slaves in the Americas and Their Links with the Atlantic World -- tPart VI. Abolition and Suppression of the Transatlantic Slave Trade -- tAfterword -- tTimeline -- tGlossary0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1501 and 1867, the transatlantic slave trade claimed an estimated 12.5 million Africans and involved almost every country with an Atlantic coastline. In this extraordinary book, two leading historians have created the first comprehensive, up-to-date atlas on this 350-year history of kidnapping and coercion. It features nearly 200 maps, especially created for the volume, that explore every detail of the African slave traffic to the New World. The atlas is based on an online database (www.slavevoyages.org) with records on nearly 35,000 slaving voyages-roughly 80 percent of all such voyages ever made. Using maps, David Eltis and David Richardson show which nations participated in the slave trade, where the ships involved were outfitted, where the captives boarded ship, and where they were landed in the Americas, as well as the experience of the transatlantic voyage and the geographic dimensions of the eventual abolition of the traffic. Accompanying the maps are illustrations and contemporary literary selections, including poems, letters, and diary entries, intended to enhance readers’ understanding of the human story underlying the trade from its inception to its end.This groundbreaking work provides the fullest possible picture of the extent and inhumanity of one of the largest forced migrations in history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSlave tradexHistoryvMaps. 0aSlave tradexHistory. 0aSlave tradezAfricaxHistoryvMaps. 0aSlave tradezAfricaxHistory. 7aREFERENCE / Atlases, Gazetteers & Maps (see also Travel / Maps & Road Atlases).2bisacsh1 aBlight, David W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, David Brion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030012460640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030018529440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300185294423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300185294/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZD